From 8d8c2008fead5b21af2a0f1ef4a73fc2b751c475 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Marcus Figueiredo <figueiredo@protonmail.com>
Date: Tue, 23 Jun 2026 16:33:51 -0300
Subject: [PATCH 6/6] virtio/gpu: defer gfxstream TransferFromHost3d to break
 dispatcher deadlock

gfxstream's pipe TransferFromHost is a blocking, full-duplex read: it spins
until the per-context RenderThread on the host produces the requested
bytes, which itself requires the guest's matching TransferToHost3d writes
(queued right behind it) to be serviced concurrently. Handling it in-line
on the single virtio-gpu dispatch thread, as every other command is,
deadlocks: that thread blocks waiting for input only it can deliver,
confirmed via `sample` showing the worker parked in
RenderChannelImpl::readBefore while a second context (e.g. the composer3
HAL) spins on DRM_IOCTL_VIRTGPU_WAIT with EBUSY.

Fix: defer TransferFromHost3d alone to a one-shot helper thread. The
gfxstream global stream_renderer_transfer_read_iov entry point is a
process-wide singleton, internally thread-safe, and reachable by resource
id alone (rutabaga_gfx::transfer_read_blocking_by_id), so the helper needs
no access to VirtioGpu for the blocking read itself -- only a brief lock
afterward to complete fencing (create_fence/process_fence). Every other
command stays on the single main worker thread, in the queue's original
order, exactly as before; only this one blocking read is offloaded, so
there is no reordering risk for anything else.

Verified via `sample`: the main "gpu worker" thread is now idle in
EventFd::read (not blocked) while a "gpu xfer" helper blocks on the
transfer, and DRM_IOCTL_VIRTGPU_WAIT EBUSY spinning drops to zero.
RenderEngine now reliably reaches GaneshVkRenderEngine::create, unlike
before this fix where it depended on lucky command interleaving timing.
